Test automation is fundamentally a decision-making system.
Your script constantly asks questions:

• Did the API return the expected status?

• Is the user logged in?

• Is the pop-up visible?

• Which environment is being tested?

• Which browser should execute the test?

• Did the actual value exactly match the expected value?
JavaScript handles these decisions using equality operators and control-flow statements such as:

• === and !==

• if

• else if

• else

• Ternary operators

• switch
These concepts may look basic, but poor control-flow logic can create false positives, flaky tests, and automation that behaves differently from what the code appears to say.
This article explains how to use JavaScript equality and conditional logic safely in real QA automation.

Equality Operators: === vs ==
JavaScript provides two commonly discussed equality operators:
==
===They may look similar, but they behave very differently.
Loose Equality: ==
Loose equality compares values after JavaScript performs type coercion.
Type coercion means JavaScript may automatically convert one data type into another before making the comparison.
Consider this:
"5" == 5; // true
0 == false; // trueThese values have different data types:
"5" // String
5 // NumberAnd:
0 // Number
false // BooleanYet loose equality returns true because JavaScript converts the values before comparing them.
This implicit conversion can hide defects in automation code.

Strict Equality: ===
Strict equality compares both:

• The value

• The data type
JavaScript does not perform type coercion.
"5" === 5; // false
0 === false; // falseThe values may look related, but their types are different:
typeof "5"; // "string"
typeof 5; // "number"Therefore:
"5" === 5;returns:
falseThis behavior is predictable, which is exactly what test automation needs.

Why Strict Equality Matters in QA Automation
Imagine an API returns the following status code as a string:
const actualStatus = "200";Your expected value is a number:
const expectedStatus = 200;Using loose equality:
actualStatus == expectedStatus;returns:
trueYour test may pass even though the API contract returned the wrong data type.
Using strict equality:
actualStatus === expectedStatus;returns:
falseThe test correctly detects the mismatch.
If the API specification says:
{
"status": 200
}but the application returns:
{
"status": "200"
}those responses are not technically identical.
A test using loose equality may hide the defect.

The Practical Rule: Prefer === and !==
For modern JavaScript automation, the safest default is:
===for equality, and:
!==for inequality.
Example:
const actualStatus = 200;if (actualStatus === 200) {
console.log("API request succeeded.");
}For inequality:
if (actualStatus !== 200) {
console.error("Unexpected API status received.");
}Using strict comparison makes your test logic explicit and predictable.

A Note About Test Framework Assertions
When using a testing framework, you often do not manually write:
actualValue === expectedValue;Instead, you use assertions.
For example:
expect(actualValue).toBe(expectedValue);In Playwright and Jest-style assertions, toBe() performs strict comparison for primitive values.
Example:
expect("200").toBe(200);This assertion fails because:
"200" !== 200This is desirable because the assertion detects both value and type differences.

Conditional Logic with if, else if, and else
The if statement executes code when a condition evaluates to a truthy value.
A typical structure looks like this:
if (condition) {
// Runs when the condition is true
} else {
// Runs when the condition is false
}You can add multiple conditions using else if.
const environment = "STAGE";if (environment === "PROD") {
console.log("Run production smoke tests.");
} else if (environment === "STAGE") {
console.log("Run regression test suite.");
} else {
console.log("Run local tests.");
}JavaScript evaluates the conditions from top to bottom.
First:
environment === "PROD"This is false.
Then:
environment === "STAGE"This is true.
Therefore, JavaScript executes:
console.log("Run regression test suite.");Once a matching branch is found, the remaining branches are skipped.

QA Application: Environment-Based Test Execution
Automation frameworks frequently behave differently depending on the target environment.
For example:
const environment = process.env.TEST_ENV || "LOCAL";if (environment === "PROD") {
console.log("Running production smoke tests.");
} else if (environment === "STAGE") {
console.log("Running full regression tests.");
} else {
console.log("Running tests against the local environment.");
}The environment could be supplied through the command line or a CI/CD pipeline.
For example:
TEST_ENV=STAGE npx playwright testThe automation framework can then dynamically change its behavior without modifying the test code.

Boolean Conditions Do Not Need === true
Suppose you have:
const isPopupVisible = true;You could write:
if (isPopupVisible === true) {
console.log("Pop-up is visible.");
}This works.
However, when the variable is already a Boolean, the cleaner form is:
if (isPopupVisible) {
console.log("Pop-up is visible.");
}Similarly, instead of:
if (isPopupVisible === false) {
console.log("Pop-up is not visible.");
}you can write:
if (!isPopupVisible) {
console.log("Pop-up is not visible.");
}The ! operator means logical NOT:
!true; // false
!false; // trueFor Boolean variables, this usually produces cleaner automation code.

QA Application: Handling Optional UI Elements
Some UI elements do not appear consistently.
Examples include:

• Cookie banners

• Marketing pop-ups

• Discount modals

• Survey dialogs

• Location permission prompts

• Promotional overlays
If one of these elements appears and blocks the page, your main test action may fail.
The test needs conditional logic.
Suppose a discount modal may appear before checkout.
In Playwright:
const discountModal = page.locator('#discount-modal');
const closeModalButton = page.locator('#close-modal-btn');const isPopupVisible = await discountModal.isVisible();The variable isPopupVisible contains a Boolean:
trueor:
falseYou can then use an if statement:
if (isPopupVisible) {
console.log("Pop-up detected. Closing it.");
await closeModalButton.click();
} else {
console.log("No pop-up appeared. Continuing test execution.");
}After handling the optional element, continue with the primary test flow:
await page.locator('#main-checkout-button').click();The complete example becomes:
const discountModal = page.locator('#discount-modal');
const closeModalButton = page.locator('#close-modal-btn');
const checkoutButton = page.locator('#main-checkout-button');const isPopupVisible = await discountModal.isVisible();if (isPopupVisible) {
console.log("Pop-up detected. Closing it.");
await closeModalButton.click();
}await checkoutButton.click();Notice that the else block is unnecessary if no action is required when the pop-up is absent.
This is cleaner:
if (isPopupVisible) {
await closeModalButton.click();
}await checkoutButton.click();
A Critical Testing Principle: Do Not Hide Real Defects
Conditional logic should not be used to make every failure disappear.
Consider this:
if (await submitButton.isVisible()) {
await submitButton.click();
}If the submit button is required by the product specification, silently skipping the click when the button is missing can hide a genuine defect.
For required elements, use assertions:
await expect(submitButton).toBeVisible();
await submitButton.click();Use conditional handling only when the element is genuinely optional.
For example:
if (await cookieBanner.isVisible()) {
await acceptCookiesButton.click();
}The distinction is important:

• Required element missing: Fail the test.

• Optional element missing: Continue safely.
Good automation should detect defects, not work around them.

The Ternary Operator
The ternary operator is a compact alternative to a simple if/else statement.
Its syntax is:
condition ? valueIfTrue : valueIfFalseExample:
const responseCode = 200;const testResult =
responseCode === 200 ? "PASS" : "FAIL";console.log(testResult);Output:
PASSThis is equivalent to:
let testResult;if (responseCode === 200) {
testResult = "PASS";
} else {
testResult = "FAIL";
}The ternary version is shorter:
const testResult =
responseCode === 200 ? "PASS" : "FAIL";
QA Application: Dynamic Configuration with a Ternary Operator
Suppose your test uses different timeouts for CI and local execution.
const isCI = process.env.CI === "true";const timeout = isCI ? 30000 : 10000;If isCI is true, the timeout becomes:
30000Otherwise:
10000Another example:
const environment = "PROD";const baseUrl =
environment === "PROD"
? "https://app.example.com"
: "https://staging.example.com";This works well because the decision is simple and produces one value.

When Not to Use a Ternary Operator
Ternary operators become difficult to read when too much logic is packed into them.
Avoid code like this:
const result =
status === 200
? role === "admin"
? "ADMIN_SUCCESS"
: "USER_SUCCESS"
: "FAIL";This is called a nested ternary.
Although valid JavaScript, it can become difficult to understand and maintain.
For complex logic, use if/else or another appropriate structure.
Use a ternary when:

• The condition is simple.

• You are choosing between two values.

• The result remains easy to read.
Use if/else when:

• Multiple statements need to execute.

• There are several conditions.

• The logic requires side effects.

• Readability begins to suffer.

The switch Statement
A switch statement compares one expression against multiple possible values.
It is often cleaner than a long chain of:
if
else if
else if
else if
elseThe basic syntax is:
switch (expression) {
case value1:
// Code
break; case value2:
// Code
break; default:
// Fallback code
}JavaScript evaluates the expression once and compares it against each case.

switch Uses Strict Comparison
A switch statement uses strict comparison semantics when matching case values.
Consider:
const status = "200";switch (status) {
case 200:
console.log("Success");
break; default:
console.log("Status did not match");
}The output is:
Status did not matchWhy?
Because:
"200" !== 200One value is a string.
The other is a number.
This is another reason why understanding data types is essential in automation.

Understanding the break Statement
A common pattern is to place break at the end of each independent case.
const browser = "firefox";switch (browser) {
case "chrome":
console.log("Launch Chrome");
break; case "firefox":
console.log("Launch Firefox");
break; case "safari":
console.log("Launch Safari");
break; default:
console.log("Unsupported browser");
}When JavaScript reaches:
break;it exits the switch statement.
Without break, execution continues into the next case.
This behavior is called fall-through.

The switch Fall-Through Trap
Consider this code:
const browser = "chrome";switch (browser) {
case "chrome":
console.log("Launch Chrome"); case "firefox":
console.log("Launch Firefox"); case "safari":
console.log("Launch Safari");
}The output is:
Launch Chrome
Launch Firefox
Launch SafariOnce the "chrome" case matches, JavaScript continues executing the following cases because there are no break statements.
For independent cases, this is usually a bug.
Use:
break;to stop execution.

But break Is Not Required After Every Case
There is an important exception.
Sometimes fall-through is intentional.
For example:
const responseStatus = 404;switch (responseStatus) {
case 200:
case 201:
console.log("API Response: SUCCESS");
break; case 400:
case 401:
case 404:
case 500:
console.error("API Response: FAILURE");
break; default:
console.log("Unknown status code received.");
}Here:
case 200:
case 201:intentionally share the same logic.
Likewise:
case 400:
case 401:
case 404:
case 500:all execute:
console.error("API Response: FAILURE");So the precise rule is not:
Every case must always have a break.
